  "opinion": "As a delivery driver in Kansas City who’s been out on the road for over a decade, I’ve seen a lot of things change, especially with how people interact online. But here’s the thing—since I don’t use social media at all, I’ve never had to deal with fake content in the first place. That’s both a blessing and a bit of a surprise to me. I know some folks worry about scams, misinformation, or even just people spreading wild rumors online, but for me, it’s not a real issue because I don’t engage with those platforms. My anxiety often makes me overthink things, though—I’ll admit I’ve been tempted to check my phone a few times when I hear about viral hoaxes or fake news stories. But I’ve learned that my job keeps me busy enough that I don’t need to dive into that world. I focus on the things I do know: my family, my hobbies like cycling and knitting, and the quiet moments when I’m out delivering packages. My kids and I have a lot of conversations about truth and trust, especially since they’re young. I tell them that if something seems too good to be true or too scary to share, it’s probably not real. For me, managing fake content isn’t about technology—it’s about staying grounded in what matters most: relationships, real-life experiences, and the simple act of being present. My high neuroticism means I can get stressed easily, but I’ve found peace in the things that don’t involve screens. If you’re anxious about fake content online, maybe it’s time to step back and focus on what’s real in your life, not what’s floating in the digital void.",
